<div id="review_2225235651" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2225235651" />
    <a title="Pamela" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30071749-pamela"><img alt="Pamela" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1509728263p2/30071749.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2225235651?book_show_action=true">Mar 30, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Pamela" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Pamela" href="/user/show/30071749-pamela">Pamela</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780330492997" href="/book/show/829793.The_Voice_of_the_Violin">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30071749-pamela?shelf=crime-italian">crime-italian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2225235651" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10803926011032743430">Montalbano investigates the brutal murder of a young woman who has been setting up home in Sicily. His enquiries involve her husband and her lover in Bologna and a local admirer who seems to have disappeared, as well as a reclusive violinist who may have secrets to reveal.<br/><br/>Probably my favourite Montalbano story, this weaves together a compelling murder mystery and an intriguing sub-plot of corruption and politics. Montalbano&apos;s character, with its blend of cunning and volatility, dominates the act</span>
  <span id="freeText10803926011032743430" style="display:none">Montalbano investigates the brutal murder of a young woman who has been setting up home in Sicily. His enquiries involve her husband and her lover in Bologna and a local admirer who seems to have disappeared, as well as a reclusive violinist who may have secrets to reveal.<br /><br />Probably my favourite Montalbano story, this weaves together a compelling murder mystery and an intriguing sub-plot of corruption and politics. Montalbano's character, with its blend of cunning and volatility, dominates the action, but the other members of his Vigata police team provide a great supporting cast - Fazio, Augello, Gallo and Galluzzo, and of course Catarella. <br /><br />Speaking of Catarella, the one odd note in Stephen Sartarelli's smooth and witty translation is that he has given him a bizarre pastiche of a New York accent, full of 'poisson' for 'person', 'wanna' and 'gotten'. I preferred the slightly buffoonish voice of the Catarella in the TV subtitles to this Sicilian who talks like a comic 'hoodlum' from a second rate gangster movie. However, the foibles of the translator in this one respect don't undermine the overall effect of a clever and subtle portrayal of Sicilian justice in action.<br /><br />Enjoyable and intelligent, this was an excellent read and I'm looking forward to the next novel in the series.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10803926011032743430" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


