<span id="freeTextContainer634962964396864301">Hey that was nice! I was expecting something that met the standard of many modern police detective stories, like the Dutch <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/807588.Pieter_Aspe' title='Pieter Aspe' rel='nofollow noopener'>Pieter Aspe</a> and <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/2904172.Toni_Coppers' title='Toni Coppers' rel='nofollow noopener'>Toni Coppers</a>, or more internationally <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/16290.Donna_Leon' title='Donna Leon' rel='nofollow noopener'>Donna Leon</a>, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/12504.Karin_Slaughter' title='Karin Slaughter' rel='nofollow noopener'>Karin Slaughter</a>, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/183956.Nicci_French' title='Nicci French' rel='nofollow noopener'>Nicci French</a> and the like. Those are generally awful and have badly written dialogue. Camilieri, however, writes rather natural dialogues and one can even imagine real people actually talking, joking and discussing with one another in that manner.<br/><br/>In this story, a beautiful young woman is found</span>
  <span id="freeText634962964396864301" style="display:none">Hey that was nice! I was expecting something that met the standard of many modern police detective stories, like the Dutch <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/807588.Pieter_Aspe" title="Pieter Aspe" rel="nofollow noopener">Pieter Aspe</a> and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/2904172.Toni_Coppers" title="Toni Coppers" rel="nofollow noopener">Toni Coppers</a>, or more internationally <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/16290.Donna_Leon" title="Donna Leon" rel="nofollow noopener">Donna Leon</a>, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/12504.Karin_Slaughter" title="Karin Slaughter" rel="nofollow noopener">Karin Slaughter</a>, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/183956.Nicci_French" title="Nicci French" rel="nofollow noopener">Nicci French</a> and the like. Those are generally awful and have badly written dialogue. Camilieri, however, writes rather natural dialogues and one can even imagine real people actually talking, joking and discussing with one another in that manner.<br /><br />In this story, a beautiful young woman is found naked in a remote villa. Also in the villa is an expensive looking violin case with a cheap, factory violin inside. Does it have anything to do with the murder, and are the woman's husband or lover involved? Read it to find out, and enjoy the energetic but also very humane way in which those Sicilians interact!</span>
